Description.LocalizedString: Though he won, he nearly bled out after the fight due to a gash along his torso.
He had travelled far and wide to reach this isolated village, hunting prey and fighting off wolves to reach his destination.
His body morphed, turning into the creature of dark tales that spread through the land like wildfire.
The ramshackle remains of a deceased hero's armor clothe the beast's burnt, stabbed, and scarred figure.
A bound and tortured monstrosity, he was dealt pain inconceivable to most humans.
Blessed armor protecting him from foes and spirits haunting warriors during the full blood moon.
His armor protected him from fire and burned everyone who dared touch it.
Its body could form armor so powerful that not even artillery could pierce it.
Pustules exuded from the gaps in his ancient armor, lighting his intimidating frame.
The eyes painted on his back never looked away.
His outfit alone intimidated his opponents.
The plastron had a haunting face that always stared down the opponent, regardless of their position.
The plastron had a haunting face that always stared down the opponent, regardless of their pleading.
He stood tall among the fallen bandits, his tunic draped loosely over him, held together by a metal belt etched with a daunting visage.
Hardened leather armor to protect him against the foes who outnumbered him five to one.

“Thank you for supporting & inspiring us along the years!” —The Dead by Daylight Team
Drunk one night, he challenged a legendary samurai to a duel.
His long ashen hair caught every flake of snow, striking fear into the hearts of children, good and bad.
He spilled the blood of farmers across the prefecture. No one could escape his wrath.
A battle-scarred bull head, fiery and animalistic in its rage, yet with enough of a human mind to express endless scorn.
Jaw broken, nose sliced off, mask smashed into his face, yet still he fought to the end.
Intricate metal work to craft a crescent-shaped helmet in honor of the moon.
While walking out from the flames, a fire trail furiously floated above him.
He took the form of a defensively-minded behemoth capable of unspeakable violence.
The excruciating pain of the procedure caused him to snap one of the horns from his head in a whirlwind of fury.
A mask he found himself wearing at the masquerade ball.
The dripping wax sealed the blindfold to his eyes.
He wore the remains of a beast.
The ominous shadow cast by the moonlight inspired terrifying tales.
The ominous silhouette against the moonlight inspired fear in the travelers.
Those who escaped in time were forever haunted by the nightmarish image of his black-horned mask.
Some locals nicknamed him 'The Imposter Noble,' for they believed his hatred for false samurai was rooted in his father's ambiguous past—in his own illegitimate bloodline.

The ancient blade he held as he bled out, whispering one final prayer. But his blood clotted and he survived as per divine intervention.
When he was allowed into the home of a wealthy swordmaker who had supplied false samurai with his wares, he launched into battle. The merchant never stood a chance.
Carved from a large, ancestral tree, his weapon was the sturdiest ever forged.
A golden sword intended to slay the minotaur, it now rests in the beast's deathly grip.
As his kanabo crumbled under the damage he wrought, he reached for his jintachi sword. It too would be ravaged by the sheer amount of bones it struck.
Ornamented blade cleansed with moon water to keep it from rust.
A blade nourished by the emanating darkness of a bloody landscape.
Its blade was as impenetrable as its skin, and just as deadly.
The foul, toxic fluid mingled and roiled with the blood of his victims.
A light blade with a steady handle.
A red sword with engraved words.
A traditional lethal weapon.
The toothed part of the blade did gruesome damage.
The toothed part of the blade shredded the bodies.
A sword with a long blade and a golden handle that requires fortitude skill to wield.

Death itself lurked in his eyes as he stared down the samurai on her loyal horse.
Unfazed by the blade that pierced his body, he travelled the land looking for a worthy opponent.
His hand fell to the grip, and he raised his weapon against the samurai on horseback.
